In the field of algorithms, sorting is one of the fundamental problems that has received considerable attention. A sorting algorithm is a comparison-based algorithm that rearranges data into a specific order, most commonly either ascending or descending. This section explores the MergeSort algorithm, which is a highly efficient sorting technique that solves the sorting problem in O(n log n) time in the worst case, where n is the size of the data set.

The MergeSort algorithm is a divide-and-conquer algorithm. It repeatedly divides the unsorted list into two halves, sorts each half, and then merges the two sorted halves. This process continues until each individual element is sorted. To merge two sorted lists, it simply compares the first elements of the two lists and places the smaller of the two elements into the merged list. This process is repeated for both lists, always comparing the first unprocessed element until one of the lists is fully merged.

